"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkdocs_site=globalThis.webpackChunkdocs_site||[]).push([[8130],{7735:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"v0210-inline-editing-mcp-autosetup","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/v0210-inline-editing-mcp-autosetup","editUrl":"https://github.com/harnspec/harnspec/tree/main/docs-site/blog/2025-12-05-v0210-release.mdx","source":"@site/blog/2025-12-05-v0210-release.mdx","title":"HarnSpec 0.2.10: Inline Metadata Editing, MCP Auto-Setup, and Multi-Project Improvements","description":"HarnSpec 0.2.10 brings a more interactive web experience with inline metadata editing, zero-config MCP setup during initialization, and significant improvements to multi-project management. This release focuses on reducing friction\u2014whether you\'re managing specs in the browser, setting up AI agent integrations, or working across multiple projects.","date":"2025-12-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"release","permalink":"/blog/tags/release"},{"inline":true,"label":"web-ui","permalink":"/blog/tags/web-ui"},{"inline":true,"label":"mcp","permalink":"/blog/tags/mcp"},{"inline":true,"label":"multi-project","permalink":"/blog/tags/multi-project"}],"readingTime":4.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Marvin Zhang","title":"LeanSpec Author","url":"https://github.com/tikazyq","imageURL":"https://github.com/tikazyq.png","key":"marvin","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"v0210-inline-editing-mcp-autosetup","title":"HarnSpec 0.2.10: Inline Metadata Editing, MCP Auto-Setup, and Multi-Project Improvements","authors":["marvin"],"tags":["release","web-ui","mcp","multi-project"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"HarnSpec Updates: Example Projects, Better Tooling, and Your Path to Getting Started","permalink":"/blog/recent-updates-getting-started"}},"content":"HarnSpec 0.2.10 brings a more interactive web experience with inline metadata editing, zero-config MCP setup during initialization, and significant improvements to multi-project management. This release focuses on reducing friction\u2014whether you\'re managing specs in the browser, setting up AI agent integrations, or working across multiple projects.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Highlights**: Edit spec metadata directly in the browser, automatic MCP configuration for your AI tools, bootstrap mode for legacy specs, and polished multi-project workflows.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## \u270f\ufe0f Inline Metadata Editing in Web UI\\r\\n\\r\\nNo more switching between the web interface and command line to update spec metadata. You can now edit everything directly in the browser:\\r\\n\\r\\n![Inline metadata editing in spec detail view](/img/blog/v0210/inline-metadata-editing.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n### What You Can Edit\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Status** - Click the status badge to change between planned, in-progress, complete, and archived\\r\\n- **Priority** - Update priority levels (low, medium, high, critical) with a single click\\r\\n- **Tags** - Add, remove, and search tags with autocomplete suggestions\\r\\n- **Dependencies** - Manage `depends_on` relationships without leaving the spec view\\r\\n\\r\\n### How It Works\\r\\n\\r\\nChanges are **optimistic**\u2014the UI updates immediately while the save happens in the background. If something fails, changes roll back automatically with a clear error message.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis works in both filesystem mode (local development) and multi-project mode (team dashboards).\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Launch the web UI\\r\\nlean-spec ui\\r\\n\\r\\n# Or with a custom port\\r\\nlean-spec ui --port 3001\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nOpen any spec, and you\'ll see the editable metadata panel on the right side.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udd27 MCP Auto-Setup During Init\\r\\n\\r\\nSetting up MCP server integration used to require manual configuration. Now `lean-spec init` handles it automatically.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Automatic Detection\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen you run `lean-spec init`, HarnSpec detects your AI tools and offers to configure MCP:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n$ lean-spec init\\r\\n\\r\\n\u2714 Detected AI tools: Claude Code, VS Code, Cursor\\r\\n\\r\\n? Configure MCP server for detected tools? (Y/n) y\\r\\n\\r\\n\u2714 Created .mcp.json for Claude Code\\r\\n\u2714 Created .vscode/mcp.json for VS Code  \\r\\n\u2714 Created .cursor/mcp.json for Cursor\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n### Zero Manual Config\\r\\n\\r\\nEach configuration file gets the correct format with absolute paths:\\r\\n\\r\\n```json\\r\\n{\\r\\n  \\"mcpServers\\": {\\r\\n    \\"lean-spec\\": {\\r\\n      \\"command\\": \\"npx\\",\\r\\n      \\"args\\": [\\"@HarnSpec/mcp\\"],\\r\\n      \\"cwd\\": \\"/absolute/path/to/your/project\\"\\r\\n    }\\r\\n  }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nYour AI agents can immediately access HarnSpec tools\u2014no copy-paste from docs, no path troubleshooting.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Supported Tools\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Claude Code** - `.mcp.json`\\r\\n- **VS Code** - `.vscode/mcp.json`\\r\\n- **Cursor** - `.cursor/mcp.json`\\r\\n\\r\\nMore tools coming soon based on demand.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udd04 Bootstrap Mode for Legacy Specs\\r\\n\\r\\nMigrating existing specs that lack frontmatter? The new `--bootstrap` flag makes it painless:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Create frontmatter for specs that don\'t have any\\r\\nlean-spec backfill --bootstrap\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n### What Bootstrap Does\\r\\n\\r\\n1. **Scans for missing frontmatter** - Identifies specs without YAML metadata\\r\\n2. **Infers status from git history** - Uses commit patterns to guess current state\\r\\n3. **Sets created date from first commit** - Accurate timestamps from your git log\\r\\n4. **Handles legacy formats** - Recognizes ADR, RFC, and inline metadata patterns\\r\\n\\r\\n### Legacy Format Support\\r\\n\\r\\nBootstrap understands common documentation patterns:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **ADR status lines**: `Status: Accepted` \u2192 `status: complete`\\r\\n- **RFC headers**: `Status: Proposed` \u2192 `status: planned`\\r\\n- **Inline metadata**: `**Status**: Complete` \u2192 `status: complete`\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Preview what would change\\r\\nlean-spec backfill --bootstrap --dry-run\\r\\n\\r\\n# Apply changes\\r\\nlean-spec backfill --bootstrap\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udcc1 Multi-Project Management Polish\\r\\n\\r\\nFor teams managing multiple projects through the web UI, we\'ve made several improvements:\\r\\n\\r\\n### Quick Access to Project Management\\r\\n\\r\\nThe project switcher dropdown now includes a \\"Manage Projects\\" option\u2014no more hunting for the projects page.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Inline Project Editing\\r\\n\\r\\nEdit project names and colors directly on the `/projects` page. Click a project name to rename it, or use the color picker to customize the visual indicator.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Better Path Handling\\r\\n\\r\\n- Long paths no longer overflow the Add Project dialog\\r\\n- Path validation shows clear status (valid/invalid/missing)\\r\\n- Invalid paths are highlighted before you try to save\\r\\n\\r\\n### Smarter Navigation\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen you switch projects from a spec detail page, you\'re now redirected to that project\'s spec list instead of getting a 404.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udcca Dependency Graph (v0.2.9 Bonus)\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you missed it in the previous release, the new `/dependencies` page gives you a bird\'s-eye view of your entire project\'s dependency structure:\\r\\n\\r\\n![Project-wide dependency graph visualization](/img/blog/v0210/dependency-graph.png)\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Interactive DAG layout** with zoom, pan, and mini-map navigation\\r\\n- **Filter by status** - Focus on planned, in-progress, or complete specs\\r\\n- **Click to navigate** - Double-click any node to open the spec detail\\r\\n- **Highlight chains** - Select a spec to see its full dependency path\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udc1b Bug Fixes\\r\\n\\r\\n### Dependencies Page Works on Custom Ports\\r\\n\\r\\nPreviously, `lean-spec ui --port 3002` would break the dependencies page due to hardcoded localhost:3000 calls. Fixed\u2014the page now works on any port.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Multi-Project Dependencies Fixed\\r\\n\\r\\nThe \\"View Dependencies\\" button on spec detail pages now works correctly in multi-project mode with a new dedicated API endpoint.\\r\\n\\r\\n### MCP `deps` Tool Finds Specs Correctly\\r\\n\\r\\nThe `deps` MCP tool now correctly resolves specs by sequence number (e.g., `045` finds `045-feature-name`).\\r\\n\\r\\n### Light Theme Contrast\\r\\n\\r\\nDependencies page nodes are now readable in light theme. We updated the color palette for proper contrast in both themes.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \u26a1 Performance: Lighter Spec Lists\\r\\n\\r\\nSpec list APIs no longer return full `contentMd` for each spec. For projects with many specs, this reduces initial page load size by ~90%.\\r\\n\\r\\nFull content loads on-demand when you open a spec detail page.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Upgrade\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Update global installation\\r\\nnpm install -g lean-spec@latest\\r\\n\\r\\n# Or use npx (always gets latest)\\r\\nnpx lean-spec@latest board\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you\'re using the MCP server:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Update MCP package\\r\\nnpm install -g @HarnSpec/mcp@latest\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n## What\'s Next\\r\\n\\r\\n- **VS Code extension** - Native spec management in your editor\\r\\n- **GitHub Action** - Automated spec validation in CI\\r\\n- **More MCP tool improvements** - Based on your feedback\\r\\n\\r\\n**Have ideas?** [Open an issue](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/issues) or [start a discussion](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/discussions).\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Links**:\\r\\n- [Documentation](https://lean-spec.dev)\\r\\n- [GitHub Repository](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec)\\r\\n- [Full Changelog](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md)\\r\\n- [Getting Started Guide](https://lean-spec.dev/docs/guide/getting-started)"},{"id":"recent-updates-getting-started","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/recent-updates-getting-started","editUrl":"https://github.com/harnspec/harnspec/tree/main/docs-site/blog/2025-11-25-recent-updates.mdx","source":"@site/blog/2025-11-25-recent-updates.mdx","title":"HarnSpec Updates: Example Projects, Better Tooling, and Your Path to Getting Started","description":"We\'ve been busy making HarnSpec easier to adopt and more powerful to use. Whether you\'re exploring spec-driven development for the first time or scaling to enterprise workflows, these updates accelerate your journey from intent to working code.","date":"2025-11-25T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"release","permalink":"/blog/tags/release"},{"inline":true,"label":"getting-started","permalink":"/blog/tags/getting-started"},{"inline":true,"label":"tutorials","permalink":"/blog/tags/tutorials"}],"readingTime":5.22,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Marvin Zhang","title":"LeanSpec Author","url":"https://github.com/tikazyq","imageURL":"https://github.com/tikazyq.png","key":"marvin","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"recent-updates-getting-started","title":"HarnSpec Updates: Example Projects, Better Tooling, and Your Path to Getting Started","authors":["marvin"],"tags":["release","getting-started","tutorials"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"HarnSpec 0.2.10: Inline Metadata Editing, MCP Auto-Setup, and Multi-Project Improvements","permalink":"/blog/v0210-inline-editing-mcp-autosetup"},"nextItem":{"title":"Why Your AI Agent Gets Dumber with Large Specs (And How to Fix It)","permalink":"/blog/ai-agent-performance"}},"content":"We\'ve been busy making HarnSpec easier to adopt and more powerful to use. Whether you\'re exploring spec-driven development for the first time or scaling to enterprise workflows, these updates accelerate your journey from intent to working code.\\r\\n\\r\\n**What\'s new**: Example projects for instant hands-on learning, JSON output for automation, simplified templates, and major improvements to our MCP server integration.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\ude80 Example Projects: Start Learning in Seconds\\r\\n\\r\\nThe best way to understand HarnSpec is to use it. That\'s why we built **example project scaffolding**\u2014complete tutorial projects you can spin up instantly.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Three Ready-to-Use Examples\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# See what\'s available\\r\\nnpx lean-spec examples\\r\\n\\r\\n# Scaffold an example project\\r\\nnpx lean-spec init --example dark-theme\\r\\ncd dark-theme\\r\\nnpm install\\r\\nnpm start\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nEach example comes with:\\r\\n- \u2705 **Complete starter code** - A working React app you can immediately build on\\r\\n- \u2705 **HarnSpec already initialized** - Specs, templates, and configuration ready to go\\r\\n- \u2705 **Realistic feature specs** - Real-world examples you can follow\\r\\n- \u2705 **Tutorial-ready** - Designed to work with our [hands-on tutorials](/docs/tutorials/first-spec-with-ai)\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Available Examples\\r\\n\\r\\n**`dark-theme`** - Add dark mode to a React app  \\r\\nPerfect first project. Learn the basics: create a spec, work with AI, track progress.\\r\\n\\r\\n**`dashboard-widgets`** - Build a customizable dashboard  \\r\\nMulti-component feature. Practice splitting specs, managing complexity, using sub-specs.\\r\\n\\r\\n**`api-refactor`** - Modernize a REST API to GraphQL  \\r\\nBackend-focused example. See how HarnSpec handles architecture changes and migrations.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Why This Matters\\r\\n\\r\\nBefore example projects:\\r\\n- \\"How do I structure a spec?\\" \u2192 Read docs, guess, iterate\\r\\n- \\"What does a real spec look like?\\" \u2192 Browse GitHub, adapt to your project\\r\\n- \\"Does this work with my AI tool?\\" \u2192 Try, debug, troubleshoot\\r\\n\\r\\n**After example projects:**\\r\\n- Clone. Run. Start coding.\\r\\n- Follow the tutorial with working code.\\r\\n- See exactly how specs guide AI agents.\\r\\n\\r\\nNo more blank-page syndrome. No more \\"where do I start?\\" Just hands-on learning with immediate results.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83e\udd16 Better AI Integration\\r\\n\\r\\n### MCP Server as Standalone Package\\r\\n\\r\\nWe extracted `@HarnSpec/mcp` into its own npm package. Setup is now cleaner:\\r\\n\\r\\n```json\\r\\n{\\r\\n  \\"mcpServers\\": {\\r\\n    \\"lean-spec\\": {\\r\\n      \\"command\\": \\"npx\\",\\r\\n      \\"args\\": [\\"@HarnSpec/mcp\\"]\\r\\n    }\\r\\n  }\\r\\n}\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nWorks with Claude Desktop, Cline, Zed, and any MCP-compatible tool. The server gives AI agents direct access to your specs\u2014no copy-paste, no context limits.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Enhanced Dependency Management\\r\\n\\r\\nNew commands make relationship management clearer:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Link specs with clear dependencies\\r\\nlean-spec link feature-123 --depends-on auth-system\\r\\n\\r\\n# See the full dependency graph\\r\\nlean-spec deps feature-123\\r\\n\\r\\n# Remove relationships\\r\\nlean-spec unlink feature-123 --from auth-system\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nBetter validation catches circular dependencies before they cause problems.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udd27 JSON Output for Automation\\r\\n\\r\\nEvery major command now supports `--json` for programmatic use:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Integrate with dashboards\\r\\nlean-spec board --json | jq \'.columns[] | select(.status==\\"in-progress\\")\'\\r\\n\\r\\n# Build custom workflows\\r\\nlean-spec list --json --status=complete | jq -r \'.[] | .name\'\\r\\n\\r\\n# Export for reporting\\r\\nlean-spec timeline --json > project-timeline.json\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nUse HarnSpec data in your CI/CD pipelines, project dashboards, or custom tooling.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83d\udcdd Simplified Templates\\r\\n\\r\\nWe removed the Handlebars templating layer. Templates are now **just markdown files** you can edit directly.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Before**: Edit `.hbs` files \u2192 Run build \u2192 Test  \\r\\n**After**: Edit `.md` files \u2192 Test\\r\\n\\r\\nTwo templates cover everything:\\r\\n- **`standard`** (default) - Single-file spec for most features\\r\\n- **`detailed`** - Multi-file example showing sub-specs in action\\r\\n\\r\\nNo build step, no template engine learning curve. Just markdown.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83c\udf0f Professional Chinese Translations\\r\\n\\r\\nIf you\'re working with Chinese-speaking teams, our docs are now fully localized with professional translations. We\'ve established strict quality guidelines:\\r\\n\\r\\n- Technical terms stay in English (Spec, CLI, Token, MCP)\\r\\n- Natural Chinese expression (not word-by-word translation)\\r\\n- Consistent terminology across all documentation\\r\\n- Full coverage of guides, tutorials, and API reference\\r\\n\\r\\nVisit [lean-spec.dev/zh-Hans](https://lean-spec.dev/zh-Hans) to see the Chinese documentation.\\r\\n\\r\\n## \ud83c\udfaf Your Path to Getting Started\\r\\n\\r\\nNot sure where to begin? Here\'s the recommended path:\\r\\n\\r\\n### 1. Understand the Why (5 minutes)\\r\\n\\r\\nRead [Why Your AI Agent Gets Dumber with Large Specs](/blog/ai-agent-performance) to understand the context engineering principles behind HarnSpec.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Key takeaway**: It\'s not about fitting in context windows\u2014it\'s about maintaining AI performance as projects scale.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 2. Spin Up an Example (2 minutes)\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nnpx lean-spec init --example dark-theme\\r\\ncd dark-theme\\r\\nnpm install\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nYou now have a working React app with HarnSpec already configured.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 3. Follow the Tutorial (10 minutes)\\r\\n\\r\\nOpen the [Your First Spec with AI](/docs/tutorials/first-spec-with-ai) tutorial. It walks you through:\\r\\n\\r\\n- Creating your first spec\\r\\n- Working with AI to implement the feature\\r\\n- Tracking progress and completing work\\r\\n- Seeing how specs guide AI behavior\\r\\n\\r\\n**Use the example project** you just scaffolded\u2014it\'s designed for this tutorial.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 4. Try Your Own Project (whenever you\'re ready)\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\ncd your-existing-project\\r\\nnpx lean-spec init\\r\\nlean-spec create user-authentication\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nNow apply what you learned. Start simple (status + created), add structure as needed (tags, priority, custom fields).\\r\\n\\r\\n### Need More Guidance?\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Small features**: [Your First Spec](/docs/tutorials/first-spec-with-ai)\\r\\n- **Multiple related features**: [Managing Multiple Features](/docs/tutorials/managing-multiple-features)\\r\\n- **Large projects**: [Large Project Management](/docs/tutorials/large-project-management)\\r\\n- **Legacy codebases**: [Refactoring with Specs](/docs/tutorials/refactoring-with-specs)\\r\\n\\r\\n## What\'s Next\\r\\n\\r\\nWe\'re focused on making HarnSpec work seamlessly with more AI tools and development workflows:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **GitHub Copilot Workspace integration** - Native spec support in Copilot\'s task planning\\r\\n- **VS Code extension** - Inline spec viewing, validation, and status tracking\\r\\n- **Project management integrations** - Jira, Linear, and GitHub Projects sync\\r\\n- **More example projects** - Backend APIs, mobile apps, infrastructure\\r\\n\\r\\n**Feedback shapes the roadmap**. What would make HarnSpec more useful for your workflow? [Open an issue](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/issues) or [join the discussion](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/discussions).\\r\\n\\r\\n## Try It Today\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Install globally\\r\\nnpm install -g lean-spec\\r\\n\\r\\n# Or use npx for one-off commands\\r\\nnpx lean-spec init --example dark-theme\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nThe fastest way to learn is to build. Pick an example, follow a tutorial, see how AI-assisted spec-driven development changes your workflow.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Links**:\\r\\n- [Documentation](https://lean-spec.dev)\\r\\n- [GitHub Repository](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec)\\r\\n- [Example Projects](https://lean-spec.dev/docs/tutorials/first-spec-with-ai#quick-start)\\r\\n- [Getting Started Guide](https://lean-spec.dev/docs/guide/getting-started)\\r\\n- [Full Tutorial Collection](https://lean-spec.dev/docs/tutorials/first-spec-with-ai)\\r\\n\\r\\n**Changelog**: See [CHANGELOG.md](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md) for detailed version history."},{"id":"ai-agent-performance","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/ai-agent-performance","editUrl":"https://github.com/harnspec/harnspec/tree/main/docs-site/blog/2025-11-10-ai-agent-performance.mdx","source":"@site/blog/2025-11-10-ai-agent-performance.mdx","title":"Why Your AI Agent Gets Dumber with Large Specs (And How to Fix It)","description":"Your spec fits in the context window. So why does your AI agent make mistakes, ignore instructions, and produce worse code?","date":"2025-11-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"ai","permalink":"/blog/tags/ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"context-engineering","permalink":"/blog/tags/context-engineering"},{"inline":true,"label":"best-practices","permalink":"/blog/tags/best-practices"}],"readingTime":7.52,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Marvin Zhang","title":"LeanSpec Author","url":"https://github.com/tikazyq","imageURL":"https://github.com/tikazyq.png","key":"marvin","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"ai-agent-performance","title":"Why Your AI Agent Gets Dumber with Large Specs (And How to Fix It)","authors":["marvin"],"tags":["ai","context-engineering","best-practices"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"HarnSpec Updates: Example Projects, Better Tooling, and Your Path to Getting Started","permalink":"/blog/recent-updates-getting-started"},"nextItem":{"title":"Welcome to HarnSpec","permalink":"/blog/welcome"}},"content":"Your spec fits in the context window. So why does your AI agent make mistakes, ignore instructions, and produce worse code? \\r\\n\\r\\nYou paste a detailed 2,000-line architecture document into Cursor. The context window can handle it\u2014200K tokens, plenty of room. But something\'s off. The AI suggests an approach you explicitly ruled out on page 3. It asks questions you already answered. The code it generates contradicts the design decisions you documented.\\r\\n\\r\\n**The problem isn\'t context size. It\'s context quality.**\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Real Problem: Performance Degradation\\r\\n\\r\\nModern AI models have massive context windows\u2014Claude has 200K tokens, GPT has 128K, and newer models are pushing toward 1M+. But here\'s what the marketing doesn\'t tell you: **AI performance degrades significantly as context grows**, even when you\'re nowhere near the limit.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe research is clear:\\r\\n\\r\\n**Databricks found** that [long-context performance degrades significantly](https://www.databricks.com/blog/long-context-rag-performance-llms) even when within theoretical limits. Smaller models degrade even earlier.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Berkeley\'s [Function-Calling Leaderboard](https://gorilla.cs.berkeley.edu/leaderboard.html)** confirmed that ALL models perform worse when given more tools or options to choose from. More context = more confusion = lower accuracy.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Research shows** ([arXiv:2505.06120](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.06120)) significant performance drops when models need to process information across multiple context turns or with increased complexity.\\r\\n\\r\\n### Why This Happens\\r\\n\\r\\nIt comes down to fundamental constraints:\\r\\n\\r\\n1. **Attention dilution** - Transformer attention has N\xb2 complexity. More tokens = harder to focus on what matters.\\r\\n\\r\\n2. **Context rot** - With large context, models start ignoring their training and just repeat patterns from the context history. They become less intelligent, not more.\\r\\n\\r\\n3. **Option overload** - Too many choices (tools, patterns, approaches) leads to wrong selections. This isn\'t unique to AI\u2014it\'s a cognitive constraint.\\r\\n\\r\\n4. **Token economics** - Every extra token costs money and time. A 2,000-line spec costs 6x more to process than a 300-line spec.\\r\\n\\r\\n### What This Means For You\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen you\'re using AI coding assistants:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Cursor, Copilot, Claude** start making basic mistakes they wouldn\'t make with smaller context\\r\\n- **Code generation** becomes less accurate and more likely to contradict your requirements\\r\\n- **Responses slow down** as the model processes more irrelevant information\\r\\n- **Costs scale up** linearly with context size\\r\\n- **You spend more time** fixing AI mistakes than you save from AI assistance\\r\\n\\r\\nThe irony: You write detailed specs to help the AI, but the detail makes the AI worse.\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Solution: Context Engineering\\r\\n\\r\\nContext engineering is the practice of managing AI working memory to maximize effectiveness. It\'s not about squeezing into context limits\u2014it\'s about **maintaining AI performance** at any scale.\\r\\n\\r\\nHere are four strategies that actually work, backed by research and real-world usage:\\r\\n\\r\\n### 1. Partitioning - Split and Load Selectively\\r\\n\\r\\n**What it is**: Break content into focused chunks, load only what\'s needed for the current task.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Example**:\\r\\n```\\r\\n# Instead of one 1,200-line spec:\\r\\nspecs/dashboard/README.md          (200 lines - overview)\\r\\nspecs/dashboard/DESIGN.md          (350 lines - architecture)\\r\\nspecs/dashboard/IMPLEMENTATION.md  (150 lines - plan)\\r\\nspecs/dashboard/TESTING.md         (180 lines - tests)\\r\\n\\r\\n# AI loads only what it needs\\r\\n# Working on architecture? Read DESIGN.md only\\r\\n# Writing tests? Read TESTING.md only\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**The benefit**: AI processes 200-350 lines instead of 1,200. Faster, more focused, fewer mistakes.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 2. Compaction - Remove Redundancy\\r\\n\\r\\n**What it is**: Eliminate duplicate or inferable content.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Before**:\\r\\n```markdown\\r\\n## Authentication\\r\\nThe authentication system uses JWT tokens. JWT tokens are \\r\\nindustry-standard and provide stateless authentication. The \\r\\nbenefit of JWT tokens is that they don\'t require server-side \\r\\nsession storage...\\r\\n\\r\\n## Implementation\\r\\nWe\'ll implement JWT authentication. JWT was chosen because...\\r\\n[repeats same rationale]\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**After**:\\r\\n```markdown\\r\\n## Authentication\\r\\nUses JWT tokens (stateless, no session storage).\\r\\n\\r\\n## Implementation\\r\\n[links to Authentication section for rationale]\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**The benefit**: Higher signal-to-noise ratio. AI focuses on unique information, not repetition.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 3. Compression - Summarize What\'s Done\\r\\n\\r\\n**What it is**: Condense completed work while preserving essential decisions.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Before**:\\r\\n```markdown\\r\\n## Phase 1: Infrastructure Setup\\r\\nSet up project structure:\\r\\n- Create src/ directory\\r\\n- Create tests/ directory  \\r\\n- Configure TypeScript with tsconfig.json\\r\\n- Set up ESLint with .eslintrc\\r\\n[50 lines of detailed steps...]\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**After** (once completed):\\r\\n```markdown\\r\\n## \u2705 Phase 1: Infrastructure (Completed 2025-10-15)\\r\\nProject structure established with TypeScript, testing, and CI.\\r\\nSee commit abc123 for details.\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n**The benefit**: Keep project history without bloat. AI knows what happened without drowning in details.\\r\\n\\r\\n### 4. Isolation - Separate Unrelated Concerns\\r\\n\\r\\n**What it is**: Move independent features into separate specs with clear relationships.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Before**: One 1,200-line spec covering dashboard UI, metrics API, health scoring algorithm, and chart library evaluation.\\r\\n\\r\\n**After**: Four focused specs, each under 400 lines:\\r\\n- `dashboard-ui` - User interface and interactions\\r\\n- `metrics-api` - Data endpoint design\\r\\n- `health-scoring` - Algorithm details\\r\\n- `chart-evaluation` - Library comparison (can be archived after decision)\\r\\n\\r\\n**The benefit**: Independent evolution. When the algorithm changes, the UI spec stays untouched.\\r\\n\\r\\n### The Key Insight\\r\\n\\r\\n**Keep context dense (high signal), not just small.**\\r\\n\\r\\nIt\'s not about arbitrary line limits. It\'s about removing anything that doesn\'t directly inform the current decision. Every word that doesn\'t help the AI make better choices is making it worse.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Real Results from Dogfooding\\r\\n\\r\\nWe built HarnSpec using HarnSpec itself\u2014the ultimate test of whether this methodology actually works.\\r\\n\\r\\n**The velocity**: 10 days from zero to production\\r\\n- Full-featured CLI with 15+ commands\\r\\n- MCP server for Cursor, GitHub Copilot integration\\r\\n- Documentation site with comprehensive guides\\r\\n- [60+ specs](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec/tree/main/specs) written and implemented with AI agents\\r\\n\\r\\n**Then we violated our own principles**: Some specs grew to 1,166 lines. We hit the exact problems we were solving:\\r\\n- AI agents started corrupting specs during edits\\r\\n- Code generation became less reliable\\r\\n- Responses slowed down noticeably\\r\\n- We spent more time fixing mistakes\\r\\n\\r\\n**We applied context engineering**: Split large specs, removed redundancy, compressed historical sections.\\r\\n- Largest spec went from 1,166 lines \u2192 378 lines (largest partition)\\r\\n- AI agents work reliably again\\r\\n- Faster iterations, accurate output\\r\\n- Can confidently say: \\"We practice what we preach\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n### Concrete Benefits You\'ll See\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen you apply context engineering to your specs:\\r\\n\\r\\n- \u2705 **Fewer AI mistakes** - Focused context produces accurate, consistent output  \\r\\n- \u2705 **Faster iterations** - Less processing time per AI request  \\r\\n- \u2705 **Lower costs** - Fewer tokens = cheaper API calls (6x savings on 2,000\u2192300 line reduction)  \\r\\n- \u2705 **Better understanding** - AI actually follows your requirements instead of hallucinating  \\r\\n- \u2705 **Maintainable by humans** - Specs you can read in 5-10 minutes stay in sync with code  \\r\\n\\r\\n### Works With Your Tools\\r\\n\\r\\nThis isn\'t about a specific AI tool\u2014it\'s about how all transformer-based models handle context:\\r\\n\\r\\n- **Cursor** - Reads markdown specs for context\\r\\n- **GitHub Copilot** - Uses workspace files for suggestions\\r\\n- **Claude** - Via MCP server integration\\r\\n- **Aider** - Processes project documentation\\r\\n- **Windsurf** - Analyzes codebase context\\r\\n\\r\\nAny AI coding assistant benefits from well-engineered context.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Getting Started\\r\\n\\r\\nHarnSpec gives you both the **methodology** and the **tooling** to apply context engineering to your specs.\\r\\n\\r\\n### The Methodology\\r\\n\\r\\nFive principles guide decision-making:\\r\\n\\r\\n1. **Context Economy** - Fit in working memory (human + AI)\\r\\n2. **Signal-to-Noise** - Every word informs decisions\\r\\n3. **Progressive Disclosure** - Add structure when needed\\r\\n4. **Intent Over Implementation** - Capture why, not just how\\r\\n5. **Bridge the Gap** - Both human and AI understand\\r\\n\\r\\nThese aren\'t arbitrary rules\u2014they\'re derived from real constraints (transformer attention, cognitive limits, token costs).\\r\\n\\r\\n### The Tooling\\r\\n\\r\\nCLI commands help you detect and fix context issues:\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\n# Install\\r\\nnpm install -g lean-spec\\r\\n\\r\\n# Initialize in your project\\r\\ncd your-project\\r\\nlean-spec init\\r\\n\\r\\n# Detect issues\\r\\nlean-spec validate              # Check for problems\\r\\nlean-spec complexity <spec>     # Analyze size/structure\\r\\n\\r\\n# Fix issues  \\r\\nlean-spec split <spec>          # Guided splitting workflow\\r\\n\\r\\n# Track progress\\r\\nlean-spec board                 # Kanban view of all specs\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n### Start Simple, Grow as Needed\\r\\n\\r\\n**Solo developer?** Just use `status` and `created` fields. Keep specs focused.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Small team?** Add `tags` and `priority`. Use the CLI for visibility.\\r\\n\\r\\n**Enterprise?** Add custom fields (`epic`, `sprint`, `assignee`). Integrate with your workflow.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe structure adapts to your needs\u2014you never add complexity \\"just in case.\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n### Try It Today\\r\\n\\r\\n```bash\\r\\nnpm install -g lean-spec\\r\\ncd your-project  \\r\\nlean-spec init\\r\\nlean-spec create user-authentication\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\nYour AI coding assistant will thank you.\\r\\n\\r\\n## The Bottom Line\\r\\n\\r\\n**Your AI tools are only as good as the context you give them.**\\r\\n\\r\\nA 2,000-line spec that fits in the context window will still produce worse results than a 300-line spec with the same essential information. It\'s not about limits\u2014it\'s about performance.\\r\\n\\r\\nContext engineering isn\'t optimization. It\'s fundamental to making AI-assisted development work reliably.\\r\\n\\r\\nHarnSpec is a context engineering methodology for human-AI collaboration on software specs. It gives you:\\r\\n- Principles derived from real constraints\\r\\n- Patterns that scale from solo to enterprise  \\r\\n- Tools that detect and prevent context problems\\r\\n- Proof from building the tool with the methodology\\r\\n\\r\\n**The choice**: Keep writing large specs and fighting with unreliable AI output, or engineer your context for the tools you actually use.\\r\\n\\r\\n---\\r\\n\\r\\n**Learn more**:\\r\\n- GitHub: [github.com/codervisor/lean-spec](https://github.com/codervisor/lean-spec)\\r\\n- Docs: [lean-spec.dev](https://lean-spec.dev)\\r\\n- Research: [Context Engineering Guide](/docs/advanced/context-engineering)\\r\\n\\r\\n**References**:\\r\\n- [Databricks: Long-Context RAG Performance](https://www.databricks.com/blog/long-context-rag-performance-llms)\\r\\n- [Berkeley Function-Calling Leaderboard](https://gorilla.cs.berkeley.edu/leaderboard.html)\\r\\n- [GraphRAG: Query-Focused Summarization (Microsoft Research)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.16130)\\r\\n- [NeedleBench: LLM Retrieval Across Information Densities](https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.11963)\\r\\n- [Context Window Performance Research](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.06120)"},{"id":"welcome","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/welcome","editUrl":"https://github.com/harnspec/harnspec/tree/main/docs-site/blog/2025-11-02-welcome.mdx","source":"@site/blog/2025-11-02-welcome.mdx","title":"Welcome to HarnSpec","description":"We\'re excited to introduce HarnSpec - a lightweight, flexible Spec-Driven Development (SDD) methodology designed for modern AI-powered development.","date":"2025-11-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"HarnSpec","permalink":"/blog/tags/harn-spec"},{"inline":true,"label":"release","permalink":"/blog/tags/release"}],"readingTime":0.7,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Marvin Zhang","title":"LeanSpec Author","url":"https://github.com/tikazyq","imageURL":"https://github.com/tikazyq.png","key":"marvin","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"welcome","title":"Welcome to HarnSpec","authors":["marvin"],"tags":["HarnSpec","release"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why Your AI Agent Gets Dumber with Large Specs (And How to Fix It)","permalink":"/blog/ai-agent-performance"}},"content":"We\'re excited to introduce HarnSpec - a lightweight, flexible Spec-Driven Development (SDD) methodology designed for modern AI-powered development.\\r\\n\\r\\n{/* truncate */}\\r\\n\\r\\n## What is HarnSpec?\\r\\n\\r\\nHarnSpec is built on the principle that **AI coding agents need clear context without overwhelming documentation**. Traditional SDD approaches either lack the detail AI needs or create so much overhead that nobody maintains them.\\r\\n\\r\\n## Key Features\\r\\n\\r\\n- \ud83c\udfaf **Write only what matters** - Clear intent AI can act on\\r\\n- \ud83e\udd16 **AI-native from day one** - Works with Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Aider, and custom agents\\r\\n- \ud83d\udcc8 **Scale naturally** - Solo dev \u2192 Small team \u2192 Enterprise\\r\\n- \ud83d\udd27 **Built-in workflow support** - Boards, timelines, dependency tracking\\r\\n- \ud83c\udfa8 **Your structure** - Custom fields, flexible templates\\r\\n\\r\\n## Getting Started\\r\\n\\r\\nCheck out our [Getting Started guide](/docs/guide/getting-started) to begin using HarnSpec in your projects.\\r\\n\\r\\n## What\'s Next?\\r\\n\\r\\nWe\'re continuously improving HarnSpec based on real-world usage. Stay tuned for more updates!"}]}}')}}]);